Tatter D'Malion<br>
Bar..Minstr..oh the heck with it <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ubrinklith.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brinklith</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#CC9900>(9/25/00 4:05:06 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/legendward/brink.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bard Question #1 - Dragons</span><hr size=1> I don't care what group you're in for a dragon: elemental and guardian with a drum.<br>
<br>
I've been in a couple of caster groups in Hate recently and I find it a real pain to decide what to sing. At 47th I'm getting resisted a fair bit by the mobs, and what buffs can you give a caster who's sitting a mile from the action?<br>
<br>
In the end I've been singing mana song and letting rip with the weapons. Dull as hell though... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><b>Brinklith Rioghbhardan</b> - Jester of Avalon<br>
<a href="http://www.geocities.com/mastersofavalon" target="_blank">Masters of Avalon</a><br>
Bard of Bristlebane<br>
<a href="http://www.brellserilis.net" target="_blank">Brell Serilis Server</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/bbrellserilis.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=daveonsilverstring>Daveon Silverstring</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Protector of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 215<br> <font color=#CC9900>(9/25/00 4:20:15 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.com/mcheeks/everquest/daveon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bard Question #1 - Dragons</span><hr size=1> In response to Deb above,<br>
<br>
In my last 20 or so levels, I've seen quite a few twink bards powerlevel past me, ignoring half their songs.  Every time I run by a group and I see &quot;XXX lets loose a bellow&quot; (or whatever the 12th level song prints out), I stop a moment to see if there's a good reason why they're not twisting in another buff/debuff instead of doing (level/2 +1) points of damage every 3 seconds.  Usually, I have to cringe because I can tell right away there's another song they could be singing instead that would help their party more (it's that much easier to tell when there is no enchanter or shaman in thier group).<br>
<br>
In my opinion, the best way to learn a class is to actually play it.  You learn a lot about how to play the bard in the mid levels, and I've seen enough bards powerlevel straight thru it without learning what to do.  Now, the rest of Norrath is starting to see what happens when you short cut the learning process...<br>
<br>
I'm not completely against twinks, as long as they learn how to play their character to be as advantageous as they can be for a given situation.  That is something bards excel at, and something that people end up missing out on when they get someone joining the group who didn't learn the ropes.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p><b>--Daveon Silverstring<br>
--Coven of Lore</b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/ukalsyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kalsyre</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#CC9900>(9/25/00 9:57:33 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bard Question #1 - Dragons</span><hr size=1> Actually, guardian is not always the best choice.<br>
<br>
For the most part, I agree, guardian is the best song to twist with Elemental rythyms (Purifying Rythyms for Trakanon).  However, VoV or Cantana can be a better selection, especially in a tank group.  Here is why:<br>
<br>
1)  At level 55 with a selos drum, just elemental alone adds 76 to Cold/Heat/Magic.<br>
2)  With gear, spells, potions, natural MR, etc... and the above mentioned bard song, many people in the group can make 255 Magic resist  without guardian, even at levels below 50.<br>
3)  VoV adds 20 AC and 30 Str which can benefit the 3 or 4 tanks in the bards group.  Not to mention if the haste spell buff is dispelled, VoV fills in quite nicely.<br>
4)  At 55 Cantana regens health for everyone, Stamina for your tanks, and magic for your clerics.  If everyone is at or near 255 MR, then Canatana will be of greater benefit then guardian.<br>
<br>
<br>
Like anything with being a Bard...you have to analyze the situation and decide for yourself what is the best way for me to help the group or the raid.   Ask yourself some basic questions... Who is in my group? What classes are they? How are they equipped? What experience do they have?  What is our foe?  What is our objective?  Where are we fighting?  Who else is on the raid?  Are there times when its actually bad for me to sing?<br>
<br>
You should also be thinking about &quot;What Ifs&quot;.  What if the monster attacks differently, what if certain people go down in my group?  What if certain people on the raid go down?  A bard is great at adapting and overcoming, so always think about the what ifs.  One of my favorite parts of playing a Bard is when your group goes &quot;OH @#$%&quot; because a &quot;What IF&quot; happend and no one is prepared...cept the bard who had thought about it in advance and happens to have the perfect song to save the day!<br>
<br>
And never be afraid to experiment.  If all you ever do is sing what everyone else sings, then we might never discover some new tactic or strategy.  I have tried alot of different songs in alot of different situations.  Experimenting is the only way to maximize your effectiveness.  I still to this day share song ideas, twist combos and raid or group tactics with bards of all levels.<br>
<br>
